multilabel classification: Squiz.Arrays.ArrayBracketSpacing is removing some comments during fixing --- As discussed in https://github.com/squizlabs/PHP_CodeSniffer/pull/1673#issuecomment-335048664, this PR addresses the `Squiz.Arrays.ArrayBracketSpacing` sniff unintentionally removing comments which were placed adjacent to the brackets.  This should not happen anymore once this PR has been merged.    Includes adjusted and additional unit tests.    While looking at the sniff, I noticed two other improvements begging to be made :heart_eyes_cat:   * The sniff still had some checks in it to prevent it acting on short array syntax. As the short array open/close brackets have their own tokens now, these checks are no longer needed.  * The sniff had a sanity check for parse errors/live coding for the close bracket, but not for the open bracket.    Both of these additional issues have been fixed in separate commits.

multilabel classification: Issues with time calculation. --- I think the routing algorithms do not properly calculate the times when turn costs are involved. Fixed in #1586.    - [x] edge-based CH does not include the turn cost times in the calculated time at all. Everything is fine for the weight calculation and when using the fastest weighting the fastest route will be found with respect to turn costs, but `Path.getTime()` will not include the turn cost times. This has to be adjusted in `Path4CH`. Fixed in #1611.    - [x] The bidirectional algorithms (dijkstra&astar, probably also ALT) do not pay attention to turn costs at the meeting point of fwd&bwd search (the turn costs are properly included for the weight calculation, but the turn cost *time* is not added when unpacking the path. multilabel classification: Method name AllEdgesIterator.getMaxId() does not describe intention --- The comment says:      I think roughly refers to the possibility of edges being marked for deletion.  I also think this is the reason why this method was named like it was, and not e.g. ``size()`` or ``nEdges()``.    However, the maximum edgeId in the graph is precisely what this method does _not_ return. It returns maximum edgeId + 1. This is relied upon in ``QueryGraph``, where ``getMaxId()`` is in fact the first edge id ``QueryGraph`` thinks it can use.    Hence, when I implement ``Graph``, take the method's name literally (which I did), and use a ``QueryGraph`` on it, I get a duplicate edge id.    Would recomment ``size()`` or ``length()``, see ``java.util.BitSet``.

multilabel classification: Add support for C++11 nullptr --- C++11 provides `nullptr_t` and a null pointer `nullptr`. It adds type safety for `NULL`, and it improves analysis in some situations. Currently, Crypto++ uses a mix of `NULL` and `0` for the null pointer. The library's use of `NULL` and `0` ensures a very dirty C++11 compile with `-Wzero-as-null-pointer-constant`. In addition, GCC is tightening the way pointers can be compared to the `nullptr` in C++11 and above.    We have an opportunity to improve it, but we need to ensure we don't break C++03. Assuming we can use `NULLPTR` as a macro, we can do something like the following. The wildcard is, will others use the `NULLPTR` macro and define it to something unexpected, like `-1`.        The choice for C++03 and `#define NULLPTR NULL` is driven by the fact `sizeof(int) != sizeof(void*)` (or they may not be equal). We are trying to avoid the wrong overload or specialization by making it someone else's problem. The someone else in this case is the compiler.

multilabel classification: AutoloadSourceLocator#locateFunctionByName should return `null` ---     This should not throw an exception, it should `return null;` instead. A source locator should not throw an exception unless something is drastically wrong (e.g. misconfiguration of it); a SL should either return the located item, or return `null` (success or fail, not error state).    It's important because the `AutoloadSourceLocator` can't autoload a function unless it's already in memory, but if you have a later source locator that *could* find that same identifier (in an aggregate), then you're breaking the chain.

multilabel classification: Return fully-fledged promise on list query count --- ## Description of changes  I am using an express middleware to share the request context with mongoose pre/post hooks, in both the public client and the admin client (with grappling hook pre:admin), without any change to keystone source code.  I noticed that each time the admin client invokes the `list/get.js` api, node **promises chain is broken**, and so the context is lost.   The issue comes from the mongoose `count` query in the async waterfall: mongoose [queries are not promises](http://mongoosejs.com/docs/promises.html#queries-are-not-promises), so we we need to use `exec()` here in order to keep the chain intact until the end of current execution.    ## Related issues  Maybe a precondition to a development of #3187 (at least from the admin ui perspective)    ## Testing    - [x] Please confirm `npm run test-all` ran successfully.

multilabel classification: Client certificate authentication --- If you're providing authentication measures, I think client-side certificate support is absolutely necessary.  At my company, we consider API tokens to be more of an identification measure. The reason being is that there's no proof of authenticity possible besides providing the token. Implementing client-side certs would solve this issue, as every single piece of communication could be signed by the sender independently, without them offering up their private keys. Obviously this would make it much harder to impersonate a user, as the impersonator would need access to the user's private keys, which are never sent over the wire.   Verifying client cert signatures should of course be left up to the webserver (apache, nginx, whatever), but the check if the provided client cert is allowed would necessarily be hug's task, as the correct client cert would be related to the identified user (through API keys or other). Moving the fixer start token determination for JS/CSS files into the fixer code block, fixes this.

multilabel classification: Username lookup needs a tuneup --- When submitting a Caffe run to an HTCondor scheduler, the job's environment is not, by default, delivered to the job environment.    This meant that the USER variable was empty in the exec node, and so glog named the log file with invalid-user in the log name created by Caffe.    This section of code needs a little TLC - currently it merely checks for a USERNAME variable on Windows and USER on Linux. While those are quick and self-contained, it would be best - if that failed - to attempt to look up the username with things like GetUserNameEx or getpwuid on the uid number.    Alternatively, instead of putting in invalid-user when a name is not found, putting uid12345 would have the benefit of preventing log name collisions between different users.    In my case it's an easy workaround, I just expressly deliver the submitter's USER environment variable to the cluster job, so this can be considered a low-priority, low-urgency issue.

multilabel classification: Generic opening brace placement sniffs incorrectly move PHPCS annotations --- As discussed in #1931, moving a trailing `phpcs:ignore` annotation to the next line changes its meaning, which is what currently happens when the `ContentAfterBrace` error is triggered by one of the new PHPCS annotations in the `Generic.Functions.OpeningFunctionBraceKernighanRitchie` and `Generic.Functions.OpeningFunctionBraceBsdAllman` sniffs.    For the `Generic.Functions.OpeningFunctionBraceBsdAllman` sniff, this also impacts the fixer of the `BraceOnSameLine` errror which could also move the comment down.    This PR fixes that.    For this fix, I've chosen to ignore *all* the PHPCS annotations, not just the `phpcs:ignore` one. If so desired, I can change the PR to only make an exception for a trailing `phpcs:ignore` comment and to move `phpcs:disable/enable/set` comments to the next line, just like normal comments.    Includes unit tests.

multilabel classification: Add SHA intrinsics when __SHA__ is not defined --- This issue tracks adding SHA intrinsics when \_\_SHA\_\_ is not defined. This happens when a machine lacks SHA or `-march=native` is _not_ used. While it may seem counter-intuitive to add it when its not needed, the primary use case is distro's, which builds for generic x86_64 and its users who have a more capable machine. A secondary use case is Clang, which does not enable _all_ cpu features under `-march=native` on occasion.    Also see [Fixing ERROR: failed to generate sha1rnds4 instruction (and friends)](https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/cryptopp-users/3ilaqjhNPv4) on the mailing list.

multilabel classification: Add ed25519 for modern signatures --- We have been dragging our feet on a curve25519 implementation. At [Pull Request 566](https://github.com/weidai11/cryptopp/pull/566) we added test code to allow us to cross-validate a real implementation, but we never provided the real implementation. The real implementation was delayed for various reasons, but one of the bigger ones was the algorithms based on the curve are hard to fit into the library the way we want it to fit.    It also looks like the IETF has provided enough information/RFCs to roll an implementation and actually interop with other libraries and software.    This is the next step in getting proper curve25519 support into the library. It provides the near-constant time curve operations optimized for 32-bit and 64-bit platforms.

multilabel classification: allow false in addition to no, fixes #1337 --- - ``no`` is a reserved word in YAML, like ``false`` in JSON  - YAML allows string values without quotes, except for reserved words  - the schema for our ``graphhopper`` configuration block is ``Map<String,String>``, we have no typesafe config yet  - so ``no`` is parsed to ``false: Boolean``, and then stringified to ``false: String``    Solution: Just interpret ``false`` the same way as ``no``. No need to do anything more general about this IMO, since the general thing we should do is move to a typed config.    Alternative: Not do this and tell users to write ``no`` or to not use YAML. But I think allowing a second reserved string ourselves doesn't hurt.    Fixes #1337

multilabel classification: Show instructions for turns onto oneway streets --- Fixes #1048.    The idea of this PR is that we show an instruction, even if the turn is the only viable turn, if there is another potential (but forbidden) turn and if the turn is not a follow road/slight turn.    The idea is that we don't see instructions when entering motorways, because these turns are usually only slight turns, but that we see instructions when turning onto a separated lane oneway as described in #1048.    One situation would be [this](https://graphhopper.com/maps/?point=-33.824437%2C151.187925&point=-33.824415%2C151.188177), but there are plenty.    So far the cases I looked at, look good. So far it feels like a good improvement. But I didn't perform too many tests yet.

multilabel classification: Switch from -O2 to -O3 in the makefile --- The makefile uses `-O2` as the default optimization level.    The source code can support `-O3` as the optimization level. In fact, we support `-O5`, `-Os` and `-Ofast`. We regularly test them in [cryptest.sh](https://github.com/weidai11/cryptopp/blob/master/cryptest.sh).    At `-O3`, GCC and other compilers will vectorize, meaning they will use SIMD units, like SSE and NEON, more frequently. When the compiler takes an opportunity it is often a non-trivial speedup.    Also see [Switch from -O2 to -O3 as optimization default?](https://groups.google.com/d/msg/cryptopp-users/AEiGyjq15tw/GBAyDA6fBgAJ) on the mailing list.

And now, you get an error because you create a static const variable using preprocessor, named this way : CEREAL_CLASS_VERSION_REGISTER##TYPE##VERSION_NUMBER. This would make it easier for us to monitor Celery automatically, because we sometimes have a task that hangs and causes all new tasks to get thrown in the queue and wait indefinitely. If there was an easy way to get the queue size (I know you can also do that with a command to the broker, Redis in our case), it would be trivial to write a script that monitors multiple servers with Celery on them through Flower, and raise warnings when a queue gets over a certain threshold.

The config.h file could have its own directory, then the `-I` compiler arg wouldn't expose more files than needed.

multilabel classification: Synchronous queue wait in multi threaded environment --- Queues in alpaka are always asynchronous to each other. In the [CPU device object](https://github.com/ComputationalRadiationPhysics/alpaka/blob/6b42f89204a6800a926b36f07d8fd2908892378e/include/alpaka/dev/DevCpu.hpp#L79-L115) we collect all asynchronous queues to allow synchronization later if [wait()](https://github.com/ComputationalRadiationPhysics/alpaka/blob/6b42f89204a6800a926b36f07d8fd2908892378e/include/alpaka/dev/cpu/Wait.hpp#L34-L59) on a device is called.      Since we added/fixed multi-thread support for synchronous queues in #786 we need the same mechanism for synchronous queues because a synchronous queue is only blocking the caller thread and the execution in one queue.    I need the same registration mechanism for we use for asynchronous queues also for a new special OMPQueue.    CC-ing: @BenjaminW3, do you have any suggestions? I currently evaluate if we can solve this issue if we create an interface class for queues and register the interfaces in the device.

multilabel classification: Disallow the use of $_REQUEST --- Like in VIP, but this makes sense generally:  https://vip.wordpress.com/documentation/vip-go/code-review-blockers-warnings-notices/#using-_request      >$_REQUEST should never be used because it is hard to track where the data is coming from (was it POST, or GET, or a cookie?), which makes reviewing the code more difficult. Additionally, it makes it easy to introduce sneaky and hard to find bugs, as any of the aforementioned locations can supply the data, which is hard to predict.  Much better to be explicit and use either $_POST or $_GET instead.

multilabel classification: Remove variable block size support for block ciphers --- Users have been having trouble with variable block sizes in practice. The problem is the implementation, and I think the root cause is a bad fit under the current library design. Reported problems on the mailing list include [Threefish-1024 IV specification issue/documentation...or bug?](https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/cryptopp-users/9-QWtfAYxB4)    The bigger engineering problem is, variable block ciphers are a bad fit under the current design. We specify security parameters, like min and max key length and iv length, as template parameters. Later we rely on virtual functions and dynamic dispatch to override the default template parameters. Worse, users have to specify the block size they want through a `Name::BlockSize` parameter because a constructor is not available to take the block size (the `SetKey(byte* key, size_t keylen, unsigned int size)` ctor was taken for variable rounds). multilabel classification: 204 No Content on HTTP/1.1 generates an empty chunk --- My code is doing:    This generates a 204 No Content, with Transfer-Encoding: chunked and includes and empty chunk '0\r\n\r\n'. But this is not valid according to the RFC2616:  10.2.5 204 No Content ... The 204 response MUST NOT include a message-body, and thus is always terminated by the first empty line after the header fields.  The Microsoft .NET HTTP Client is upset by the extra chunk being sent. The only work-around is to disable keep-alive by adding Connection: close to the request.

multilabel classification: Add OldRandomPool for pre-Crypto++ 5.5 compatibility --- We are still seeing users stuck at Crypto++ 4.2, Crypto++ 5.2, and other down level versions. The sticking point appears to be the old PGP style `RandomPool` generator. The PGP style `RandomPool` is effectively a deterministic generator and it was used as a deterministic  key derivation function. See, for example:    * [Migrating from Crypto++ 5.2.1 to Crypto++ 5.6.5](https://groups.google.com/d/msg/cryptopp-users/lVtQizUAtlY/dH5Goc60AgAJ)  * [Moving from Crypto++ 4.2 to Crypto++ 5.6.4](https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/cryptopp-users/lVtQizUAtlY)    While we discourage the old PGP style `RandomPool` generator for several technical reasons, we should not allow it to be a barrier to a modern Crypto++ upgrade. The lack of a clear migration path and non-interoperability is a security engineering failure on our part.    This issue will track the addition of `OldRandomPool` to give users a clear and interoperable upgrade path.

multilabel classification: MMapDataAccess should synchronize on its ByteBuffers by itself --- - MMapDataAccess now synchronizes on its ByteBuffers by itself, and is now as thread-safe as the other implementations. (That is, mostly, except for create/close/ensureCapacity and such.)  - Remove the dimension of synched or not synched from DataAccess.  - Remove tests which tested this dimension.  - Remove some unused code.    Benefits:    - One whole concept less.  - Clarifies that we do read/write locking externally, i.e. on the layer of GraphHopper, not on the layer of DataAccess.  - Cannot accidentally be made incorrect by using more than one (reading) thread without using _SYNC.    Drawbacks:    - Possibility of being slower when running single-threaded because of the overhead of synchronized{} blocks _as such_, without thread contention. No idea how likely that is.      Counter-argument against drawback:    - That is not as bad as being *generally* thread-safe *except* with certain parameters.      How can I test Android performance?

That means than when a smart pointer with non-default deleter or allocator is de-serialized, it's not going to behave the same as the original version. <not good>  At a minimum, cereal should raise an exception if a smart pointer with non-default deleter or allocator is submitted for serialization.  A similar problem exists with STL containers.  Most (all?) of them allow customer allocators.  So they should raise an exception also.

If a `Generator` function does not support `Generator::send()`, i.e. no assign-from-field (`$foo = yield;`), then `T2` should be required to be `void`.    If a `Generator` function does support `Generator::send()`, then `T2` should support type-hinting other than mixed [without triggering MixedTypeCoercion](https://getpsalm.org/r/0eb120fa6e) (although it does currently correctly trigger `InvalidScalarArgument`). multilabel classification: not possible to use Websocket as a client with a self-signed server certificate --- Currently the Websocket class does not provide a means to ignore any SSL errors.  This is usually only a problem when using a QSslSocket as a client with a server that uses a self-signed certificate (need to ignore QSslError::SelfSignedCertificate). Additionally on some builds of QT 4.x on windows, QT may report QSslError::NoError and forces the user to ignore it in order to continue (bug in QT).  I suggest a new method `WebSocket::setExpectedSslErrors(QList<QSslError>&)` which would store the list in a member variable. In case all the error codes of SSL errors QT reports in `WebSocket::onSslErrors` are in the expected list, call `qobject_cast<QSslSocket*>(sender())->ignoreSslErrors(m_ignoreList)`, otherwise do what it does now.  To clarify, it is possible to use the current Websocket class with a self-signed certificate as a server, but not as a client.

multilabel classification: Application using log4cplus hangs on exit --- With relatively latest log4cplus version (commit from 04122015) I have encountered unexpected hang in my application upon exit. After two days of digging, I have found that ThreadPool destructor is called twice:    As you can see, all worker threads have gone. And the second one:    As you can see log4cplus::Hierarchy::shutdown tries to destruct already destructed ThreadPool instance. It happens because of fields order in struct DefaultContext (from global-init.cxx):    thread_pool member is destructed before hierarchy member. As result, we are in trouble. Several solutions possible: 1) change member order 2) remove explicit ThreadPool shutdown from Hierarchy

multilabel classification: Fixing AutoloadSourceLocator when multiple PSR-0/4 directories are possible --- This PR fixes #384.    The issue was that Composer autoloader is scanning the PSR-4 directories that may contain the file.    **Composer's ClassLoader.php excerpt**:      The call to `file_exists` was always returning `true`, because of the way the `AutoloadSourceLocator::url_stat` was written.    I reimplemented the `url_stat` to actually unregister the stream wrapper, fall back to the real stream wrapper, do the real stat call and then re-register the stream wrapper.    The code is strongly inspired from PHP-VCR so thanks to PHP-VCR folks for the idea :)    Note: The first commit is a failing test to demonstrate #384 issue.

multilabel classification: Remove MAINTAIN_BACKWARDS_COMPATIBILITY_562 --- Crypto++ 5.6.3 cleared a number of issues uncovered by analysis and testing tools. To maintain compatibility with Crypto++ 5.6.2, `MAINTAIN_BACKWARDS_COMPATIBILITY_562` was introduced. It allowed us to clear _most_ of the findings while maintaining compatibility. If `MAINTAIN_BACKWARDS_COMPATIBILITY_562` was not defined, then _all_ the issues were mitigated.  Future version of Crypto++ will not need `MAINTAIN_BACKWARDS_COMPATIBILITY_562` because compatibility with 5.6.2 is not a concern. That is, Crypto++ 5.7 or 6.0 will not need it because advancement is expected, and there are no guarantees. Also see [Release Versioning](http://cryptopp.com/wiki/Release_Versioning) on the Crypto++ Wiki.  Distributions, like Debian and Fedora, are currently incorporating 5.6.3. In about 30 days, we should remove `MAINTAIN_BACKWARDS_COMPATIBILITY_562` so GitHub users enjoy the most stable code.  ---  We should also remove warning suppression of C4505 from `config.h`:

multilabel classification: Speck, Android and Linux kernel interop --- The Linux kernel added Speck-64 and Speck-128 for opportunistic encryption on low resource devices that would otherwise have to disable encryption on the file system. Also see [[PATCH v2 0/5] crypto: Speck support](https://www.mail-archive.com/linux-crypto@vger.kernel.org/msg30925.html) on the kernel-crypto mailing list.    The problem is we are not going to interop well with the kernel. The problem is due to confusion in the Simon and Speck algorithmic description and the test vectors. The algorithmic description and test vectors did not quite align, and we went down one path (follow the test vectors) and the kernel went down another path (follow the algorithmic description).    It is possible to to interop with the kernel using our implementation but... (1) it is not readily apparent how to do it, and (2) there's a loss of efficiency when doing it. multilabel classification: Request and Response Object can be deleted at every time --- I openend this as a own issue. I came over it while stress testing the threading code with autobench/httperf. And i found 2 problems but they come both from the same source:  Httperf opens lots of connections at the same time and runs requests on the server. Every request has a timeout and if the timeout is reached it just closes the socket.  This may be no problem with the non threaded version ( i didn't check yet) but in the  threaded version you have pending requests if the server load is high.  They are waiting in a queue, the problem is if they reach the connection timeout the  sockets are closed and deleted WHILE they are still waiting. Also we don't have socket error handling code (a error maybe should emit some signal and close the  request).  This creates two problems:  1) If you call flush on a closed socket you get a SIGPIPE termination. HttpFileHandler runs into this because it does not enter the eventloop when writing  multiple times to the socket. This can maybe be fixed

multilabel classification: <yield> tag suddenly requires closing tag or slash --- In previous versions (eg. This change was seemingly introduced in `2.3.16`. Previous versions did not have a `reYieldAll` regex defined.  **How would you tag this issue:** Bug.

multilabel classification: Add CRC intrinsics when __CRC__ is not defined --- This issue tracks adding CRC intrinsics when \_\_CRC\_\_ is not defined. This happens when a machine lacks CRC or `-march=native` is _not_ used. While it may seem counter-intuitive to add it when its not needed, the primary use case is distro's, which builds for generic x86_64 and its users who have a more capable machine. A secondary use case is Clang, which does not enable _all_ cpu features under `-march=native` on occasion.    Also see [Fixing ERROR: failed to generate sha1rnds4 instruction (and friends)](https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/cryptopp-users/3ilaqjhNPv4) on the mailing list.

multilabel classification: Zeroizer may be removed if assembler is not available --- This apples to the library in general, and the intersection of assemblers and compilers. It was recently brought to light with Clang testing.  Clang has an integrated assembler that's not quite as mature as it needs to be. There are 5 or 6 LLVM bugs that affect Crypto++ (cf., 18916, 24200, 24226, 24232 and a few others). When the assembler is disabled, the library disables the inline assembly code paths that perform the zeroization and leave it to C++ statements.  C++ statements with volatile are somewhat ambiguous because the meaning of volatile is not well defined in the standard. See, for example, Ian Lance Taylor's blog at http://www.airs.com/blog/archives/154. In fact, the Crypto++ code has comments regarding work arounds due to GCC optimizing out a write of 0 on occasion.

multilabel classification: Add Random Number Generator benchmarks --- This fell out of a [conversation on Stack Overflow](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/26771329/is-there-any-legitimate-use-for-intels-rdrand/33090047?noredirect=1#comment72217241_33090047). Crypto++ does not perform RNG benchmarks. In addition, <strike>Botan and</strike> OpenSSL does not offer a way to test RNG throughput in their respective tools.    In the big picture, I am interested in learning how well RDRAND and RDSEED performs against other generators, like those provided by the OS in `BlockingRNG` and `NonblockingRNG`. I'm also curious about OpenSSL's `md5_rand` (used by default), and the Kernel's proposal to use ChaCha and SipHash based generators for `/dev/urandom` (the kernel claims equivalent security and improved speed/efficiency).    RDRAND and RDSEED seem especially tricky to test. David Johnston of Intel suggested we test RDRAND and RDSEED with [Colin King's StressNG](https://www.google.com/search?q=Colin+King+StressNG).

multilabel classification: Discrepancies between isValid and normalizeEmail --- So there are situations where isEmail will return `true`, but normalizeEmail will return false.    For example:    `+123456789@gmail.com` -> isEmail returns true, normalizeEmail returns false.    Really this comes down to a behavior that I think the library should enforce:  > If isEmail returns true, normalizeEmail should be able to return a value    Currently `normalizeEmail` can return `false`, which seems wrong. It feels like if `normalizeEmail` can't do what it needs to it should return the original string or `null`?    ### Extend isEmail?    Currently normalizeEmail is actually doing domain-specific email validation as well as normalizing the email. For example +123456789@gmail.com is syntactically valid, but invalid for gmail. Maybe `isEmail` should also be extended to contain this domain-specific logic to bring it into line with what normalizeEmail is doing.

multilabel classification: Response time graph seems to be an average of all data --- ### Description of issue / feature request    In the web UI, the response time graph seems to show response time for the entire test run, which I feel is unsuitable for a graph format. At a given x-point on the graph, the current graph shows the average of all data up until then, whereas it would be more useful to see the average of data at that time.    ### Expected behavior    Response time might be better displayed as a moving average rather than a complete average.    ### Actual behavior    Response time is calculated as an absolute/complete average rather than moving average, which means spikes are significantly 'dampened'. This also doesn't seem to fit a graph format - an absolute average would be suitable for a single number (e.g. the Statistics tab) and a moving average would be better suited for a time-based view like a line graph.

multilabel classification: Opened IOStreams should always be closed with IOSystem::Close --- Currently most importers use `unique_ptr<IOStream>` or directly `delete` the opened `IOStream`. The `IOSystem::Close` function is not called.    This is bad, because it only works, if the `IOStream` returned by `IOSystem::Open` actually was allocated using `new`. If my custom `IOSystem` implementation would use a different allocator, then this would fail catastrophically.    By always calling `IOSystem::Close` this could be avoided. The `IOSystem` knows how to allocate the `IOStream`, therefore it should also know how to deallocate this resource.

multilabel classification: Add KeyDerivationFunction interface --- This has been a long time coming... We have not really moved forward into the newer password hashing algorithms because we lacked the infrastructure to do so. In the old days we only needed to manage salts and iteration counts. Nowadays we have several additional parameters, like hardness factors.    The additional parameters beg for a `KeyDerivationFunction` interface that accepts a `NameValuepairs` to pass arbitrary parameters in an extensible way. While not readily apparent, a `KeyDerivationFunction` interface also provides unified testing of the algorithms using test vectors. The base interface allows us to provide factory methods to create a KDF without the need of knowing a particular constructor. The KDF is then configured using `NameValuepairs`.    This ticket will track the addition of the `KeyDerivationFunction` interface and the associated changes for existing KDF's and PBKDF's.

multilabel classification: Emit warning when a matching method collides with defined mappings. --- We now have the possibility at root level to instruct MapStruct how to behave. However, this might collide with pre-existing (non forged) mapping methods.     So supposed we have   1. a nested target AND   2. MapStruct was supposed to forge a mapping method at the current nesting target entry to the source according to the mapping definitions at root level AND  3. There is a pre-existing source method that should have been selected otherwise.    Then we have a conflict. The `@Mapping` annotations collide apparently with the user intention. See #1090 for example.     We should emit a warning or perhaps even an error in that scenario. The user is supposed to: either define stuff with `@Mapping` at the root level OR define their own mapping methods (with their own `@Mapping` annotations or even implemented methods). Mixing leads to unpredictable behavior.    NB. This can be solved in the `PropertyMapping`.

It could be avoided by updating component deps before building the box phar with `platform: {php: 5.3.3}` in `composer.json` file ([example](https://github.com/FriendsOfPHP/PHP-CS-Fixer/blob/1.11/.travis.yml#L48-L52)).  Sadly, I cannot help more as phar file is built outside Travis (probably locally by project maintainers).

multilabel classification: Remove template parameter `Archive` from `InputBindingsMap` and `OutputBindingsMap` --- `Archive` isn't directly needed for any content in binding  structs and required only to instantiate different global static  maps for different archives.    This commit turns `InputBindingsMap` and `OutputBindingsMap` into  non-templated structs and modifies binding maps to include archive's  typeid, such that they describe relation: `typeid(Archive) ->  per-archive binding map`.    That way only two global static objects will be created in runtime (for  input and output bindings respectively) in each library/executable. Also  types of these globals are independent from included archives and known  beforehand.

multilabel classification: Signal when routing / bypassing on router and any piped routers? --- I had a requirement to know when a router has successfully routed (or has bypassed) both itself and for any piped routers it has attached.  This allows for a global 404 handler to be attached, or otherwise.  It should function for any depth of router hierarchy.  I patched crossroads as per below, providing a routedOrSubRouted signal - it actually fires after each parse() with a true/false if a route was found - so is more like a route or bypass event.  I needed to set ignoreState = true on all routers.  Otherwise when parsing a previously found route, the routed signal doesn't fire, and this code assumes no route was found.  If there's less messy way to achieve this (or similar functionality a consideration for a pull request), please let me know!  p.s. multilabel classification: Invalid serialization fails silently for polymorphic types --- When a polymorphic type is registered, cereal attempts to find compatible serialization functions for that type with all currently registered archives. For every match, cereal creates a lookup entry that can be used at runtime to correctly route the polymorphic serialization.  If there is a problem matching the type to any archive, it silently fails since there may be a match with a different archive type.  This creates a situation in which cereal will not be able to catch an invalid serialization at compile-time:    Unfortunately I can't think of a great solution to this - emitting an explicit failure would cause issues if someone included an archive that was not compatible with their type prior to registration. If registration was only done in source files, this might not be a big deal, but registration can also be done in header files, where it is much harder to control previously included files.  We could also try to emit an error if there was not at least one working type-archive

multilabel classification: Rename interpolate to expand --- The URI template syntax used by routes is very similar to the one proposed with [RFC 6570](http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc6570). The RFC uses the term `expand` to describe the operation of expanding a URI template with given variables; since Crossroads implements this functionality with the `interpolate` method, renaming it to `expand` (leaving `interpolate` as an alias for backward compatibility) would make this excellent plugin closer to the specification and least but not last would save characters when typing the method name.

multilabel classification: Maximum Nodes Exceeded Exception --- This fixes #1188. I added some more exceptions to GH to make it easier for the client to show appropriate help to the user.    Something interesting I found along the way was that in the GraphHopperServlet, we did not catch all RuntimeExceptions but only IllegalArgumentExceptions. Is this desired? I changed this to catch RuntimeExceptions. I would understand the argument, that users should not be notified about exceptions other than IllegalArgument, because it's not their fault. The API returned a 500 html document, maybe we catch all RuntimeExceptions and return a generic json error then?    I also changed a couple of other exceptions a bit. I think the overall goal should be to convert the most common exceptions into GHExceptions so the client can improve the parsing of these exceptions.

multilabel classification: URL: Content after a hash is validated --- Related to https://github.com/chriso/validator.js/issues/613    The following URL's are valid:  - http://a.ca#id 1  - http://a.ca#>Here  Even though they have a space an a < or > symbol, this should work   Both of these will correctly move the navigator towards the related ID.    Those aren't considered a valid URL by the regex here:  https://github.com/chriso/validator.js/blob/master/lib/isURL.js#L49    ` /[\s<>]/.test(url)`  I would suggest only testing the part before the hash if one is present, instead of the whole URL. Users shouldn't rely on being a valid URL to consider it safe for HTML.

multilabel classification: write().csv() closes its writer in all circumstances --- If a CsvWriter object is created using CsvWriteOptions.Builder initialised with a file name, I can understand why the CsvWriter closes its writer when finished. However, if CsvWriteOptions.Builder is initialised with an OutputStream, the caller may want to use the stream for something else afterward, so I'd like to suggest that the CsvWriter not automatically close the writer when done in that instance. Flush it, by all means, but don't close it. (Might need in that case to make it possible for the client to extract the writer so it can be closed later, or provide a separate close() method).    The context here is I have a large number of Table objects being generated at unpredictable intervals, and I wish to dump each one in turn to a single file as each becomes available. Merging all the results into one table before dumping is not practical because of the sheer size of the final results, and because it would mean waiting until the very end before I get any results at all to look at.

multilabel classification: Road Elevation Smoothing --- This PR fixes/approaches #517.     The problem with GH currently is that the elevation data contains spikes and the overall calculated ascend and descend are sometimes wrong by a factor of two or more.    Because of the increased calculation of ascend and descend, the distance can be wrong as well, because GH calculates the distance of a road using lat, lon, and elevation.    This PR proposes a rather simple approach. Before adding an edge to the graph, we smooth it's elevation, removing most spikes. Take the geometry of the edge and for every pillar but not tower node of the geometry, look at the surrounding points and calculate the average of these points.    **TODO**:  ~~I am not sure if it would be better to rate points that are farther away with a lower weight?~~ I tried this briefly and this led to worse results. multilabel classification: Optional Collector: should work also when application not reachable --- If you use the collector to monitor a couple of clusters of application servers, there are problems when some or all application servers of a cluster is not reachable. E.g. if there was a crash, javamelody is sometimes very useful tool to find out what happened. But as it is, you can't view its data until the crashed monitored server is running again.   Another usecase is that you could make a backup of the data directory and start a collector server later on another machine to view this historical data. This doesn't work now, since the collector wants to connect to the monitored servers (which would actually be harmful in this usecase).

multilabel classification: Prohibits the locustfile from being named 'locust.py' --- Fixes #138    This PR prohibits naming your locustfile `locust.py`, which previously caused Locust to exit with a misleading message (No Locust class found).    The new behavior is to exit with a more helpful error message explaining not to name the file `locust.py`.     The issue was occuring because the locustfile gets imported as a Python module (with the .py extension removed).  So naming it `locust.py` caused a namespace clash with the internal `locust` module, which would get re-imported instead of the locustfile.      Note: This only fixes the common case where you have named it `locust.py`.  There are also other reserved names that can not be used as locustfile names.  We might want to add something to the docs to explain this.

multilabel classification: Tooltip chartContainer defaults to document.body, which breaks tooltips with other chartContainers --- Apologies if this has been reported already. There's a lot of tooltip bugs, but I don't think this particular one is listed.  Charts without `useInteractiveGuideline` use tooltips without giving them a `chartContainer`, which defaults to `document.body`. This is a problem because in `initTooltip`, there is a line `d3.select(container).selectAll('.nvtooltip')`, which selects all the tooltips on the page, including ones from other charts, and the rest of the function breaks the other tooltips in unpredictable ways.  Charts with `useInteractiveGuideline` set the `chartContainer` to `parentNode`, which works perfectly fine with any other chart. But if we don't want `useInteractiveGuideline`, we have to manually set the tooltip `chartContainer` in order for tooltips not to break.  Why not just make all the tooltips default their `chartContainer` to `parentNode`?

multilabel classification: Using the '--sniffs' argument has a problem with case sensitivity --- When using the '--sniffs'  argument with phpcs you have to enter the the sniffs case sensitive for the sniff to work.  However when using any other casing (like all lowercase) of the same letters, phpcs will not fail.  Instead it will find the sniff and run it, but it will never report any errors.  If different letters are used, phpcs obviously complains directly that it can't find the sniff.    This is since the matching of errors to sniffs is done with in_array(), which is case sensitive. But the loading of sniffs uses strtolower() in various places.    So this patch makes the '--sniffs' argument fully case sensitive.

multilabel classification: Suggestion: Texture baking postprocess. --- Is there any chance that a new assimp texture baking postprocess could be added? multilabel classification: Linux shared-object library versioning --- Changes to do shared-object library versioning on Linux. The soname is based on the major and minor version numbers, and presumes patchlevel updates are safe to use with binaries compiled and linked against older patchlevels. Mainly that means header files don't change significantly across patchlevels. If that's not the case, the soname would have to have the patchlevel added to it and the link creation/removal code involving SOLIB_COMPAT_SUFFIX has to change.

multilabel classification: Parameterize Column with element type --- I suggest declaring Column as **class Column<T>** where T is the element type (same for CategoricalColumn), and fixing the API accordingly. This will allow cleaner and more generic code, but there are also some issues:  - overloading methods with native types, e.g. **set(int row, double value)** and **set(int row, Double value)** are allowed, but **double get(int row)** and **Double get(int row)** cannot co-exist, hence a different name may need to be invented for the generic methods  - missing values must be handled, e.g. null must be mapped to MISSING_VALUE by methods like set and append  I made a working implementation in an hour that passed all tests.

multilabel classification: Add CRYPTOPP_NO_CXX11 for old compilers --- Around Crypto++ 5.6.3 we started adding C++11 and above support. It has been modest, like using C++11's `alignof` and `alignas` instead of platform specific features like `declspec` and `__attribute__`.    One area that has been painful is threading and synchronization. Some older compilers claim to be a version of C++ they are not, like C++11 when they are really just C++03 with some additional headers. Older Apple platforms and MinGW falls into this category. I has been a constant sources of problems on some platforms, MinGW.      We work around Apple, but MinGW continues to be a problem (from [`config.h`](https://github.com/weidai11/cryptopp/blob/master/config.h#L892):        We need an easy way to turn off C++11.    This issue will track two commits. First is the addition of a `CRYPTOPP_NO_CXX11`, and second are the supporting self tests to ensure it works.    -----    Here are some problem reports from the field. We should have recognized this trend sooner and moved against it.

multilabel classification: Virtual DOM in tagline may be misleading --- - [x] Question - [x] Discussion  After reading Virtual DOM in the tagline, I was a bit confused reading this on the compare page:  > Riot takes the expressions from the tree and stores them in an array. Each expression has a pointer to a DOM node. On each run these expressions are evaluated and compared to the values in the DOM. When a value has changed the corresponding DOM node is updated. In a way Riot also has a virtual DOM, just a much simpler one.  That sounds like the _real_ DOM is scanned for any out-of-date values. I checked the source and it does indeed appear that Riot is [looping](https://github.com/riot/riot/blob/master/riot.js#L1818) through [old/new value comparisons](https://github.com/riot/riot/blob/master/riot.js#L1833). To me, that's the definition of _dirty checking_. I think the way most people use the term virtual DOM, it's actually referring to the creation of a virtual copy of the DOM, which is used to diff against _in place of_ the real DOM. multilabel classification: Compiler warning due to different string alignments in mqueue.cpp code --- I use Visual Studio 2017 (msvc15) under Windows 10 and Crypto++ 6.10.  I get the following linker warning:        I know that is the Microsoft compiler problem and I reported it to them.  But I also know why It occures and there is a very simple way to avoid it.    In your code, in `mqueue.cpp` we have    `return Output(1, (const byte *)\0, 1, 0, blocking) != 0;`    The string `\0` is actually a two-element array of two zero bytes - exactly the same as `L`. So the problem is whether it is a 1-length char* or an empty wide string.    Maybe you can write  `return Output(1, (const byte *)\0\0, 1, 0, blocking) != 0;`  or  `return Output(1, (const byte *), 1, 0, blocking) != 0;`    Both codes works the same way and without linker warnings.    P.S. Older versions of Crypto++ give the same effect, of course.

multilabel classification: Binary Attributes Double-base64 Encoded --- The botocore client, called via [`_convert_to_request_dict`](https://github.com/jlafon/PynamoDB/blob/devel/pynamodb/connection/base.py#L247), is performing another round of base64 encoding on binary fields. This is on top of the existing round of encoding done by the BinaryAttribute's [`serialize()`](https://github.com/jlafon/PynamoDB/blob/621b90aab64e14d274289e4e5684926f340bc48c/pynamodb/attributes.py#L100) method.  This is resulting in **double base64 encoded** values stored in Dynamo, which is why we have to undo one of the decodes via [`_convert_binary`](https://github.com/jlafon/PynamoDB/blob/master/pynamodb/connection/base.py#L956).   IOW, all binary data that has ever been persisted using the BinaryAttribute in any version of Pynamo is sitting double-base64-encoded in Dynamo somewhere.

multilabel classification: Use `px` for line-height --- Yea yea yea [I know we already looked at this](https://github.com/TedGoas/Cerberus/issues/138) but I'm changing my opinion based on a few recent conversations. _Technically_ `px` and `%` both work when inlined (not inherited), but since unit-less `line-height` is not supported by Outlook, we can't count on `line-height` being correctly inherited. For the correct `line-height` to display consistently, `line-height` should be inlined on every element. `%` and `px` both work when inlined, but `%` gives the impression that the cascade should work when it doesn't.

multilabel classification: Add AES intrinsics when __AES__ is not defined --- This issue tracks adding AES intrinsics when \_\_AES\_\_ is not defined. This happens when a machine lacks AES or `-march=native` is _not_ used. While it may seem counter-intuitive to add it when its not needed, the primary use case is distro's, which builds for generic x86_64 and its users who have a more capable machine. A secondary use case is Clang, which does not enable _all_ cpu features under `-march=native` on occasion.    Also see [Fixing ERROR: failed to generate sha1rnds4 instruction (and friends)](https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/cryptopp-users/3ilaqjhNPv4) on the mailing list.

multilabel classification: Squiz.PHP.DisallowMultipleAssignments false positive in while loop conditions --- A variable assignment in the condition of a `while` loop may well be enclosed in additional parenthesis to prevent issues with operator precedence when comparing the assigned value within the same condition. multilabel classification: Make line-numbers styles more specific --- The padding added to `pre.line-numbers` in the line-number's CSS is  overwritten by the theme's CSS if the theme is loaded second. This  ensures the CSS can come in any order without specificity issues.    I ran into this problem in the settings page for WP-Gistpen, where the  user can toggle the theme and enabled plugins. Switching between themes  removes the CSS for the previous theme from the head and injects the new  theme into the head, so the line-numbers CSS actually appears in the  head _first_. The theme CSS that sets the padding uses `pre` while the  line-numbers `pre.line-numbers`, and who wins is whomever  comes second.    There's also some whitespace cleanup here as well.    I think this is unlikely to be a breaking change, but interested in feedback on this.

multilabel classification: Generic/MultipleStatementAlignment: fix bug/list syntax before assignment operator --- This simplifies the fixes which were previously committed to fix #1870 and #1848, which were released in `3.2.3`.    Both those fixes try to prevent the sniff getting confused over (potentially) multi-line value assignments, such as closures and arrays.    The simplification removes the previously added code in favour of skipping to the end of a statement as soon as an assignment operator has been found.    This might also make the sniff marginally faster as the tokens between the assignment operator and the end of the statement will no longer be examined.    N.B.: The reason for going one back from the end of the assignment (line 241), is that otherwise the code addressing the issue covered by the unit test on line 220 / added in commit 579d39cac3163bdf05ce1b50a7e470acd452735b would not be triggered, leading to incorrect results.    Fixes #1922    Side-note: I think it would be a good idea to add unit tests for the `File::findEndOfStatement()` method.

multilabel classification: URLs with more than 2 slashes after protocol incorrectly considered valid --- Currently (as of 7.0.0) validator `isURL()` considers an URL such as the following to be valid:    http:///mashable.com/category/kim-kardashian    Note the triple-slash after the protocol.  Adding more slashes also passes `isURL()`.  According to spec, only two slashes should be used in a valid URL.    Chrome (as of v57) and Firefox (as of v52) and Safari for iOS will still navigate to the URL with the extra slashes, but Safari for OS X (as of 10.0) will not, instead rewriting the url to be `localhost/mashable.com/category/kim-kardashian`.    This feels like a bug in Safari, but since the URL technically isn't valid to begin with and browsers are only being forgiving by navigating to them, it seems like `isURL()` should not consider these URLs to be valid.

We've tested the change with toy programs, and we would like to solicit feedback from real projects using Crypto++.     The 3 second tour is as follows. From 10,000 feet, Crypto++ plans on moving `byte` from the global namespace into the Crypto++ namespace. multilabel classification: @template-extends expects multi-line input --- It appears that the docblock parser expects template-extends to be a multi-line annotation entry if the line following the declaration consists solely of a single *.    There's a php-cs-fixer rule (`phpdoc_separation`) that requires annotations of differing types be separated by a blank line.    If one declares the template annotations first, followed by property annotations, then the issue occurs.  The workaround is to declare `@template-extends` last, as the docblock parser likely interprets `*/` as there's no more annotations, go home.    Unless the docblock is parsed backwards, I suspect non-workaround solution to this may be impacted by/benefit from #1518 as docblock annotations *may* be valid at the start of a line in a multi-line annotation (e.g. a multi-line version of `array{@property:string}`).    * expects-multiline: https://psalm.dev/r/0077af5d32  * doesn't expect: https://psalm.dev/r/315044f3c9      > Psalm output (using commit 624c7bc):   >  > ERROR: InvalidDocblock - 12:

The function is used at multiple places  > throughout the code, so the bug *might* have security implications, hence  > I'm reporting via email.  >  > misc.h:748 incorrectly assumes that the maximal value of type T1 is  > SIZE_MAX/sizeof(T1), which causes RoundUpToMultipleOf to detect integer  > overflows incorrectly. multilabel classification: Improve using glog as cmake subproject --- Some glog users like to include it in sources and use `add_subdirectory`. However, that results in a problem: `install()` commands are processed and may interfere with other things.    Here's a concrete scenario:    - `gflags` is included with `add_subdirectory`, therefore `gflags` target is defined (as `ALIAS` in fact)  - `glog` is included the same way, with `WITH_GFLAGS=OFF`, but `gflags_FOUND=ON`. This way `find_package(gflags)` does not run (which would fail), but `gflags` support is activated and `target_link_libraries(glog gflags)` runs successfully, because the target is defined    However, when `glog` calls `install(TARGETS glog EXPORTS glog-targets...)`, cmake wants `gflags` target installed in the same export set and, of course, fails.    I propose to use the same workaround used in `gflags` project: add cmake option `GLOG_IS_SUBPROJECT` and, if it's defined, do not call any `install()` commands. This way consuming project will be able to link to `gflags` static library with

multilabel classification: AEAD interface doesn't support offline AEAD algorithms --- Our AEAD interface `AuthenticatedSymmetricCipherBase` (defined in `authenc.h`) doesn't support AEAD modes of operation that aren't online, i.e. offline ciphers.  For those of you, how don't know what online and offline mean in this context:  > A cipher is colled online if the encryption of the i-th input block M_i depends only on the blocks M_1,...,M_{i-1} and only constant size-state is used from the processing of one block to the next. We call an AEAD scheme online if its encryption algorithm is an online cipher and its decryption algorithm is its inverse operation. Schemes that are not online are called offline.  Now most modern ciphers are online (yay!), but there's one particularly interesting class of ciphers that are proven to be _always_ offline: _fully nonce misuse resistant authenticated encryption schemes_. If you use one of those schemes and re-use the nonce, all an attacker can tell is whether you encrypted the same message whereas with other modes the attacker can either

Psalm interprets`@internal` as meaning that the declaring and calling code must not be in 'unrelated namepsaces', and emits issues as shown at https://psalm.dev/r/90a95c1dd8 . multilabel classification: Allow http-transform-pattern aggregation to match regex groups --- Currently the value set by the [http-transform-pattern](https://github.com/javamelody/javamelody/wiki/UserGuide#6-optional-parameters) parameter in the web.xml will transform descriptions of http requests by replacing all matches found by the regular-expression, including all matched groups, by a $. This will always include group 0 which will be the whole string that matches the regex pattern. This makes aggregation very limited since it will always aggregate the entire match of the regex pattern regardless of what group you're trying to match.       Perhaps changing the logic of getAggregateRequestName in javamelody-core/src/main/java/net/bull/javamelody/internal/model/Counter.java to take into account different groups instead of using  matcher.replaceAll(TRANSFORM_REPLACEMENT) would work.
